WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Okay, so today is Wednesday, April 17th. We are in Seattle, Washington. This is David Cline from Virginia Tech.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:34.000
And the Smithsonian Museum of African American History and Culture, the Library of Congress, and the Southern Oral History Program.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Today, I am doing the interview along with John Bishop, who is our videographer of Media Generation and UCLA.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:50.000
And today, we have with us Reverend Dr. Samuel Berry McKinney. And thank you so much for joining us today.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Thank you.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Reverend McKinney, if we could start, if you could tell us a little bit about your childhood, the family you were born into.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:14.000
And I know that you were born into a church home with a strong civil rights background. So I'm curious to hear how that shaped you as you grew up.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:29.000
My name is Samuel Berry McKinney, as was indicated. I was born December 28, 1926 in Flint, Michigan.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:47.000
My father was a Baptist minister who was born in, outside of Gainesville, Georgia on July 19, 1892.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:02:09.000
And he was one of 12 children. His father, Wade Hampton McKinney, and there was my father's name also, and my brother. And his son was a Georgia sharecropper.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:21.000
We would move in, we would move into Georgia from South Carolina.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:38.000
When my father was 18 and in the fifth grade, he was encouraged by his pastor of the St. John Baptist Church in Gainesville, Georgia.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:45.000
The father of his education, he was 18 and in the fifth grade.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:03:00.000
So he went to the Atlanta Baptist College in 1910, which became Morehouse College in 1914.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:19.000
And I have somewhere, his high school certificate. Because at that time there were not many public high schools for blacks or color and negro, whatever we happen to be at that time.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:43.000
And it was usually in the private sector of schools which were organized by many fair-minded people after the Civil War to educate the reason for the freedom of people bounding and slavery.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:04:01.000
He, in 1916, received his high school diploma and in 1920. He graduated from Morehouse College with a B.A. degree.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:11.000
He was accepted at the Rochester Theological Seminary in Rochester, New York, where he continued his education.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:24.000
But let me back up just a little bit so you can get a flavor of what was going on at Morehouse at the time.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:36.000
I indicated that there are many people who came south to try to help the people who recently freed from slavery.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:46.000
In 1881, two sisters from...

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.000
I wanted to recall this first grade. We're rolling again.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
So you were talking about Morehouse?

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Yes. It was really organized in 1867. And it was a Augusta Baptist College. And then it moved to Atlanta and became Atlanta Baptist College.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:21.000
And in 1914 it became Morehouse College, named for Henry Lyman Morehouse, who had been the executive of the...

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:30.000
It was then the Northern Baptist Convention, later to become the American Baptist Convention that we know today.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:43.000
A lot of young people and many others came south white to join in that movement to train and educate many people.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:52.000
Two young ladies came down from New England and then tried to think of the school they attended.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:03.000
But they organized a college for women in the basement of the Friendship Baptist Church in Atlanta. And it became Spelman College.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:13.000
They were modeled after the Harvard-Yale. I know they would have a university for men in a college for women.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:18.000
And Spelman was the fittings of that category.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:42.000
These two sisters, (Sophia B.) Packard and (Harriet E.) Giles, I can't remember their first names, called upon one of their schoolmates who had married Laura Spelman Rockefeller, to help fund this school.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:50.000
And Spelman College was Spelman Seminary until 1929.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:07:00.000
In 1929 there was quite a merger of schools in the country.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
So many people appealed to Rockefeller for help.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:14.000
He sat down and came over the Grand Master Plan instead of having all these schools where we can combine them and let's do so.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
So that's where Union Seminary in New York came into being.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:31.000
But in Atlanta there were several black institutions and they didn't lose any of their autonomy.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
They were asked to work together in a unified fashion.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:46.000
So the Atlanta University system was organized with the Morehouse as the component for men, Spelman, for women.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:08:00.000
They were still independent. Atlanta University would be a graduate school and they had to fight to retain that name in Atlanta because others wanted that name to be more associated with white and black.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:20.000
I'm saying all that to say that in 1916 a young lady from Birmingham, Alabama named Annie Ruth Berry McKinney McKinney, my mother, came to Spelman.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:29.000
She was the youngest of six children and four girls all who had attended Spelman.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:37.000
Spelman did not become a college until 1929.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.000
I mentioned about the Rochester Theological Seminary in 1929.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:55.000
It combined with Colgate. Colgate, a hundred some miles from Rochester, had a division of training ministers, were training ministers.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:03.000
So it moved to Rochester and it became Colgate. Rochester beginning back to Spelman.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:12.000
My mother ended up in Spelman Seminary in 1916.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:22.000
She became one of 13 or 17 women who technically graduated from Morehouse, which was a college.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:30.000
Spelman didn't become a college until 1929.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:40.000
Rockefeller poured a lot of money into Spelman and it filtered out to the other schools.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:46.000
My parents met on the campus because they had a lot of classes together.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Her background was a little different. My father came up for a boy's father was a sharecropper.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:09.000
My mother's father was a Baptist minister and many of blacks at that time listened to Booker T. Washington who said to let down your bucket where you are".

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:17.000
let down your bucket where you are, build where you are, strengthen the land where you are.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And let your roots down, where you are, what it brought down to.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And many people in Alabama took that seriously.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:35.000
My grandfather was one and he sent my own to a lot of land and gave it to his children.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:41.000
I don't know what my mother did with hers, but when I asked about it she ignored me.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
So in other words, we won't touch that.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:11:00.000
But when Dr. King marched from Selma to Montgomery, every place he stopped along the way was on land that was owned by black people.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:06.000
So he was not an intruder at any point.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
And that was well-planned out.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:25.000
Yes. And there are people who question and rightly so some of the philosophy of Booker T. Washington being as separate as fingers out but yet united.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:31.000
He did not sit well with a lot of people and still does not.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:36.000
But he didn't insist upon people looking out for themselves and owning land.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And this on the stem of grandfather did.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:50.000
So my parents met there and my mother finished one of 13 or 17 women who technically finished the Morehouse.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And that was in 1921.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:57.000
I was going to say, but you also at the same time you're talking about your grandfather on your mother's side.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
He also insisted that sounds like that his children even had the same childhood as that in education.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
Yes.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:16.000
One son, the older son, went to Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, which at that time was like Morehouse All-Mail.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.000
But it's co-ed now.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
The next son, James, was sort of a rebel.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
And I guess that happens in most families.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:37.000
He stayed in Birmingham and worked for the Tennessee Iron and Coal Company.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:45.000
They're in steel worker until he retired and passed.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:57.000
So my mother's older sister, my mother's mother, died when my mother was two years old.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
And so their older sister, who was 17 years old,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:09.000
was feeling in help to rear her and set some standards for her.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:16.000
And they became part of what some sociologists have called Black puritans.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:29.000
Women and black women who were built against the notion that any black woman was fair, pray for any white man sexually.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:37.000
They wanted to make sure that their children did not fall prey to that sort of doctrine.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And they stood for religious and moral purity in every way.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:55.000
And so when my father asked my aunt for my mother's hand,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:00.000
he had to jump through a lot of hurdles for her.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:06.000
But she did live in 1829. She came to live with the family.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:07.000
I'm saying all that.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:18.000
And my mother also finished Columbia Teachers College and taught at what is now Jackson State.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.000
It was Jackson College and Jackson Mississippi.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:29.000
And then in the school that no longer exists Roger Williams College in Nashville, Tennessee.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And that's where she was teaching when she and my father married.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:44.000
My father's first church was in Flint, Michigan, Mount Olive Baptist Church.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
He went there in 1923.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:53.000
They married in 1924.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
My brother showed up in 1925.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
I came along in 1926.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:11.000
In 1928, my father was called to the Antioch Baptist Church.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:22.000
A church he served for 34 and a half years until he passed in January, 1963.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:35.000
Although he was the retirement, the end of 1962, he passed 18th of January, 1963.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:39.000
He served that church well.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:45.000
But going back to his college,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:57.000
the only places where the blacks who attended the Abidic schools could teach were in the historically black colleges.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:04.000
And so the persons who were able to get an education at the Abidic schools had to go south.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And many of them brought their ideas and things they had been exposed to.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:23.000
One of the strong things that came into Morehouse was the emphasis upon social justice,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:32.000
making society better and making people better and abiding people to stand erect on their feet.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:43.000
So Dr. John Hope, who was president of Morehouse for many years,

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
I think he was president during my father's 10 years.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:51.000
He looked like a white man and some people thought he was.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:58.000
So he was able to walk a whiteer than the B.C.P. to move through some circles and societies

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
and some people didn't even know he was there.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
They were looking for this colored man.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:10.000
He was looking too, but they just set some standards.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:22.000
They were then planned within this school, a desire for justice, the best training possible.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:34.000
So the emergence of somebody like Martin Luther King Jr. was not a surprise.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:40.000
So that's when my father came up and what he was exposed to.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:43.000
Was there rooting in the social gospel?

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
Yes.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
And they...

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:53.000
How would you describe what that means, what the social gospel is?

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
It means seeing...

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:07.000
It's based upon, in the Old Testament, this 61st chapter of Psalms,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:16.000
is what Jesus quoted and is recorded in the fourth chapter of Luke of the Spirit of the Lord God is upon me

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:28.000
because he is anointed me to preach the gospel, to free the captives, to set at liberty of those who are bound to declare the acceptable year of the Lord.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:39.000
And after Jesus read that in his hometown, he closed the book up and handed it back to the attendant and said today,

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:43.000
this has been fulfilled in your hearing.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:54.000
During that period when my father was in college, there was a fellow who taught a roucher,

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:59.000
a roucher theological seminary for a while, a Walter Rauschenbusch.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
You heard of that name.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:09.000
He was declared one of the apostles of the social justice,

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:21.000
gospel, setting it in liberty, freeing up people who have been bound and to declare the truth.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:33.000
And so my father came up under that kind of instruction, although Rauschenbusch died while he was still a student.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:42.000
Rauschenbusch Mark was left on quite a number of the students and others.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:56.000
And the person who became president of Morehouse four years before I entered there was Dr. Benjamin Elijah Mays,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:08.000
who was out of South Carolina, (Bates?) Virginia (?), Bates College, then Union Theological Seminary, and then earned the PhD from University of Chicago.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:13.000
And he was a president when I was there.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:17.000
I was entered in 1944.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:30.000
And at age 17, when I became 18, Uncle Sam was on me, and I tried to avoid it,

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:40.000
the process of escaping wasn't as defined as it is now.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:52.000
One of the classmates, one of the fellow freshmen, was a fellow from Atlanta, a little fellow,

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
because of him.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:00.000
Squirt, named Martin Luther King Jr. was in the same freshman class.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
He was 15.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:10.000
I'm not saying anything from him, but he was able to enter college at that age because World War II was on.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:18.000
Students and enrollments were down, and especially in an all male institution.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:24.000
We as freshmen noticed that we're over 400 of us, and only 50 of a classmate.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.000
So some of us decided there would be no hazing.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:30.000
No freshmen, we had numbers.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:34.000
We had the numbers to back it up.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:42.000
But in the state of Georgia, they came up with the idea to boost enrollments that if you,

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:49.000
and it wasn't limited to men, that if you took a test in the 11th grade and passed it,

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:57.000
you could go automatically, you could bypass the 12th grade and go directly into college.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
And that's what Dr. King did.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:05.000
It's just the Christine King Farris King Farris King Farris, who's the only surviving member of the family,

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:09.000
was right on time with her entrance.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:14.000
So the college is the same time and graduated at the same time.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:18.000
What was 15-year-old Martin King like?

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:28.000
I guess any other 15 year old, but he was what they called a city student.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:33.000
He lived in the city, and he was driving a car before a motion.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:37.000
So he drove to the campus.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:46.000
It's interesting to note that to my knowledge, he took part in every oratorical contest and never won.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:52.000
That's kind of hard to believe, but it happened.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:23:00.000
He then went to Crozer Theological Seminary right outside of Philadelphia.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:08.000
And from that, Boston University, and we have talked about it and laughed about it,

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:15.000
I had the opportunity to go to the church in Montgomery before he did.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:18.000
And that's only ought to be lay up for the movement.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:29.000
It didn't happen because I did not have, at that time, a commitment to nonviolence.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:34.000
I grew up in Cleveland, Ohio. I was 18 months old when my father went there.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:42.000
And it was there that I saw him speak out against injustices.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:58.000
Work on programs and efforts to open doors for people in the same spirit of the social justice movement.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:02.000
If there was injustice, he just didn't turn you back and walk away from it.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:05.000
You adjusted it, at least undressed it.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:10.000
So people could see it and know about it.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:14.000
Your father had hosted some great minds at his church in Oakland.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:18.000
He was about every few minutes and said, okay, we're back.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:23.000
Was just as curious who came as guest to your father's church.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:35.000
Well, he had people like A. Philip Randolph, Walter White of the NAACP.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:48.000
Many people of that statue of the Mordecai Wyatt Johnson who was president of Howard University at that time,

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:51.000
and also a more house graduate.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:56.000
And sort of a mentor, older brother figure, to my father when he was in college.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:03.000
He had people like that, so I heard a lot of these people growing up.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:13.000
And there was an organization, Future Outlook League. stood for Future Outlook League,

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:23.000
that had campaigns in Cleveland that don't patronize places where you cannot work.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:28.000
And that challenged a lot of people.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:31.000
They had milkmen back in that day.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.000
You know, left a bottle of milk on a broad doorstep.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:39.000
But the boycott of that until he broke down the...

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
Early boycott.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:56.000
The challenge of Cleveland Transit System, just before World War II broke out and hired people.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:01.000
I remember a lot of buildings big, you know, to bond like buildings.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:03.000
I didn't know what they were.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:09.000
When World War II started, all the lights went on.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:13.000
And they were producing things for the war effort.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.000
And a lot of people went to work.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:26.000
There was another massive influx of people from the South.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:39.000
And my parents were part of that when they called one of the first major round World War I to take part in the movement of Northwood.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:44.000
In fact, no father was in the army for 59 days.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
So it's England and the World War I.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:51.000
And long enough to get some benefits from that.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:57.000
They approximate what it was like after World War II.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:02.000
That's the best G.I. Bill that the country has had.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:18.000
I think if you can disrupt people's lives and put them into the least you can do is to give them an education or a job or something.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:27.000
My brother and I were both able to finish college on the G.I. Bill.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:32.000
So you were just talking about you being drafted and you ended up in the Army Air Corps?

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:37.000
It was Army Air Corps. The Air Corps, it's now Air Force.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.000
It's a separate unit.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:59.000
But the G.I. Bill was, if you were in military service on September 2, 1945 when the war officially ended, you were entitled to one full year on the G.I. Bill.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:07.000
After that, one month for each month you were in service, not to exceed 48.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:13.000
So that made it possible for my brother and I both to finish college on the G.I. Bill.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:23.000
And my father could save his money from assistors when they went to college.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:32.000
Could I ask a little bit about what it was like serving in the segregated military at that time?

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:44.000
It was what I'm describing like this.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:50.000
I was in a segregated Army the whole time I was there.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:29:05.000
After we had finished basic training at Sheppard Field, Wichita Falls, Texas, we were shipped to some of us, we shipped to the Yuma, Arizona.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:11.000
And the train took a security route to get from Wichita Falls.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:23.000
It went far west then, south to El Paso, then across New Mexico, Arizona.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:38.000
But we did stop, it'll come to me, down in West Texas, where we stopped, the train stopped and we got off for lunch break.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:42.000
This was in pre-plastic days.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:49.000
We had cardboard plates wooden forks and somebody said, hey, come here and look.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:56.000
We looked from where we were in the colored dining room, in the white dining room.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:04.000
There were tablecloths, then in the silverware and German prisoners of war.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:11.000
Sitting down to the table eating, we had on the United States Army uniform.

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:18.000
And these were supposed to be enemies of our country, because they were white.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:23.000
That's how they were retreated, where they were treated.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:31.000
And no respect for us, and I asked somebody, I was up-sid with what I saw.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:36.000
I asked somebody, how far was it from where we were to Cleveland?

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:40.000
They said about 1800 miles.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:44.000
And they asked me, are you thinking about going AWOL?

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:48.000
I said, I'm thinking about going AWOL.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:31:00.000
That sums up a good bit of a re-wrapping the army, but in a segregated unit in the air force.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:10.000
And on the basis where we were, well, if you want an air force base.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:21.000
And in an listed person, you did not have to salute anybody under captain, because you had to be an officer to fly a plane.

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:28.000
And you'd been walking around like that all the time, but except when they made new loose ends.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:37.000
And they made the last class, or you know, when we were there, sure that we got there.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:40.000
Somebody said, land a bicycle, what?

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:51.000
They said they had the habit of giving a dollar to the first enlisted man who saluted them.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:58.000
So you should have just said, you have to be a dollar with this hand.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:10.000
But they had people assigned to the various units based upon what they did.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:20.000
For instance, if you were a mechanic on the land, they all stayed together, except they had what they called a squadron F.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:25.000
Where all the blacks, whatever they did, had to stay there.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:34.000
And I found out I was part of the overhear for the squadron F.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:47.000
It was not a good or happy feeling.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:54.000
And no one respected us with the uniform on.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:59.000
Go with on and off to the base. Did you get to go after me?

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:09.000
Oh yeah, yeah. But they had in town the colored USO, white USO, and had to stay there.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:16.000
We went to a ship from Arizona to the biggest field, California.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:22.000
And we discovered one thing, we could hit the ride into town.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:27.000
You had no trouble getting from town back to the base.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:30.000
But there were a lot of southern whites up in that area.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:38.000
Also, we would land up outside the gates, you know, and you'd drive away from.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:45.000
And I noticed that one night I was the only person left out there.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:50.000
Most of the colors were from places in the south.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:53.000
And most of these whites were to get in here.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:58.000
And I found when I said I was from Ohio, I was left out on the road.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:03.000
And I said, well, the next color comes by here, I'm going to be from Mississippi.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:07.000
And that's what I said, getting in here from Mississippi.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:10.000
And he asked me questions, I couldn't answer.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:13.000
I asked him so I'd fake sleep.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:17.000
And he found I asked where I was getting out of that toilet.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:32.000
But they stopped shipping blacks of color, but we were known as then to Europe.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:39.000
And then stopped shipping us overseas.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:46.000
I mean, over to Asia as well.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:58.000
And then we would ship from the biggest field of California all the way across country down to Florida.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:14.000
And people were reenlisting so fast that I didn't notice when I first went in that the regular army on payday.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:20.000
The regular army was paid first.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:39.000
And then the more people that re-enlisted, the further back, the lowest private in the regular army was paid before the top civilian army as they called it other army of the US.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:43.000
That's what most people were doing during the war.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:46.000
And we finally came up with some things.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:56.000
And one of them was everybody drafted in 1945 had to be out by Christmas of 1946.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:36:07.000
So I was able to figure out how much time I had left.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:13.000
And when back to school, I didn't have enough time to start all over again.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:17.000
So I was in a pre-law track.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:20.000
So I followed that until I graduated from college.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:28.000
And I went to Colgate Rochester, Divinity School, and Rochester, New York for three years.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:31.000
Did you think you would pursue the law at one point?

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:36.000
I was at plan to be a lawyer.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:46.000
But then Morehouse was a historic religious institution so there was a required course in Bible that was taken.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:51.000
George Kelsey.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.000
I don't know.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:56.000
Sometimes people say you're preaching to me.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:59.000
I didn't know but he was speaking to me.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:07.000
In fact, a lot of fellows were thinking about being lawyers.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:13.000
And some of them were considering the ministry and how were they going to reconcile the two.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:22.000
And then he said, the law can only function after something has been done.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:29.000
For instance, as a woman who's complaining about being harassed,

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:37.000
brutalized by a husband or male friend, and the police will say,

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:41.000
well, I can't help you until he hurts you.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
Sometimes it's too late.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:50.000
He said, the law functions on the back end, religion functions on the front end.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:56.000
And as one thinks so, one is, thought proceeds action.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:02.000
And somehow I couldn't shake that or the analogy that he used it.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:05.000
What should you do?

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:14.000
Put an ambulance in the valley to take people after they've fallen over the cliff to the hospital or put a pothole.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:17.000
So people don't fall off.

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.000
Well, that resonated.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:26.000
And I couldn't shake that and understand that had an impact on others as well.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:31.000
Did you get to know Dr. Mays, as well?

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:35.000
He influenced quite a number of us.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:43.000
He told us, when we first got to school and there were a lot of World War II was on,

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:51.000
there were a lot of white women who were driving buses and street cars and he told us

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:58.000
not to get into any argument, but if we had a problem with the person male or female,

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:06.000
make a mental no quickly of their name and badge number and get off and come back and tell him about it.

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:18.000
And we did. We found out that his contacts in New York and Atlanta has really been outposted.

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:30.000
Benjamin Elijah Mays was president of Morehouse from 1941 to 1967.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:42.000
And not only kept these traditions of high scholarship and speaking of truth and justice,

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:46.000
but he modeled a lot of it.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:57.000
And there were those who said that anybody who had come up in the school under Dr. Mays could have done what King did.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:12.000
And he just agreed with that because when we were growing up, Joe Louis was a heavyweight champion.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:23.000
A lot of people, they were riding on his face and his victories.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:36.000
The mother sister, Anita, our totals, was caught up in this puritanical thing of her.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:40.000
She felt that boxing was sinful.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:45.000
And then I told you know, Joe Louis was born in Alabama.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:53.000
Then she was from Alabama. She still didn't like it, but she listened to it.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:58.000
When he was fighting, it was like a nice warm summer day.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:09.000
People found the longest extension cord and would bring the radio, this before television, out of the front portion.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:12.000
You could walk them down the street and not miss a thing.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:19.000
It was going on the same thing happened when Jackie Robinson went into the baseball.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:25.000
I grew up in Cleveland, which was in the American League. And Larry Doby was the first black.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:36.000
He was on Cleveland, seen many American League. You would walk up in down the street and not miss anything.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:46.000
When Joe Louis knocked the (Max) Schmeling out, we had an ex-dome neighbor who, in my aunt, were very good friends.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:54.000
They thought alike. She got out on the front porch because she could have stand that sinful boxing.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:58.000
And she had a sister who was visiting her from Mississippi.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:02.000
And that lady had to wear close to 400 pounds.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:06.000
she literally shouted the front porch down.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:14.000
And we were pulling the porch back in the days. But she just was so happy.

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:20.000
Now a lot of blacks could not celebrate like that in the South.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:26.000
A very kind and simple black man beating up a white man.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:29.000
So...

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.000
But did people celebrate behind closed doors?

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.000
Oh yes.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:35.000
Oh yes.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:42.000
But we arrived in the street and went back to the milling. It had been one of Hitler's boys.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:53.000
So the Jewish community supported the celebrations of his defeat.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:59.000
And this was an impactful time.

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:07.000
We had a famous neighbor who lived about five to six doors north of us.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:15.000
I never saw him there, but his mother and father and younger brothers and sisters because of Jesse Owens.

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:18.000
They lived in Cleveland.

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:21.000
I never saw him in the house.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:31.000
But you know it's the impact that they would have, but kids going up and down the street when they got in front of his house would stop on your mark.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:35.000
You know, get set, go. He wanted to see you.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
Run with that impact.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:41.000
The presence was something.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:48.000
And that's the kind of impact we had at that time.

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:52.000
We were still finding these various role models.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:54.000
Yes.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.000
And...

00:43:56.000 --> 00:44:00.000
I think it was a very important door to the crew.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:02.000
And they did...

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:05.000
Oh, it's for us, right?

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.000
For that?

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:08.000
Okay.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:12.000
Yes.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:21.000
I'm saying all this to say that I grew up in a community that seems at the...

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:25.000
to see the avenue YMCA and Cleveland.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:28.000
That's how I had his hand on.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:34.000
Or could it touch just about any black youth in the community?

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:45.000
And that was very, very helpful.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:56.000
So when you went to seminary then, did you have a sense already what kind of a ministry you would be called to?

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:58.000
Yes, I am.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:08.000
The models that I had had been folks like my father and some of his friends and liked Dr. Mays

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:16.000
And Mordecai Wyatt Johnson who was the president of Howard University was also a Baptist preacher.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:25.000
And many of the folks I was exposed to, I didn't know them all, but many of those I was exposed to.

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:30.000
With those worth...with emulating.

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:38.000
And that's what I wanted to do, the idea of a megachurch.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:45.000
Oh, that was unheard of then, although there were large churches.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:52.000
And my father's church had...at the height of his ministry, had over 3,000 members.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:46:02.000
And he would also bring, I think from 1936 through 46.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:08.000
He brought for the church anniversary in January, Adam Clayton Powell Jr.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:14.000
So got exposed to people like that.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:21.000
Remember when he became the pastor of the church.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:27.000
And when he was the next to the City Council in New York, then Congress.

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:43.000
So I was exposed to people of that nature that Dr. Mays would bring to the campus as often as he could people that he felt would be a great source of inspiration.

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:48.000
To the students.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:54.000
So that's a good part of my life, I don't know which...

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:59.000
And did you stay in touch with Martin King after he went on the crotor you went on...

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:04.000
You went into the army or the Air Force and then on to Samaritan?

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:07.000
Yes, he...

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:14.000
He made one trip to Seattle at an invitation.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:18.000
And that was the last time he traveled by himself.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:23.000
Because he told me the near misses and escapes he had had.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:28.000
He was sure that there were some assassins out there.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:34.000
But after he came here, this was...

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:41.000
He said after his trip here was his last trip anywhere by himself.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:45.000
We invited him here at the...

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:50.000
to speak of the brotherhood of the church.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:52.000
And he accepted it.

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:58.000
And this was in 1961.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:05.000
In 1962, we had a big world spare here in Seattle.

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:14.000
So what is now the Seattle Center was kind of under construction while that event.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:20.000
So we knew that our facilities were too small to house in.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:27.000
And the fellow who was the executive of the Presbytery of Seattle suggested that

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:34.000
I approach (First) Presbyterian Church, Seattle, which is downtown Seattle.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:42.000
They had an old facility at that time that had seen it over 3000.

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:48.000
And we were given what I thought was a solid,

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:53.000
an antecedent agreement and understanding.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:49:02.000
And then when we got closer to the time and started advertising,

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:13.000
I got a letter from the ruling body of the church stating that

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:16.000
you could not have the event there.

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:24.000
Because we had not followed the proper protocol and signing up to use it all of that.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:27.000
So we asked for a meeting.

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:32.000
And we went to the meeting and several of the men from the church.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:40.000
And the fellow who was the head of the church council of Presbyteria, whatever they called it,

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:46.000
I guess he was about six-two-and-a-half, flowing, you know, white hair, he was a lawyer.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:51.000
We had the kind of boy that could strike fear in the judge and the jury.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:55.000
You know you did not follow protocol.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:57.000
You're going to do this or do the other.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:02.000
And therefore you cannot have use of this.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:05.000
So you understand that and we didn't answer.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:08.000
But he said it anyhow.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:16.000
And then he tried to soften his tone, said, but we know that you spend some money on your

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:18.000
advertisements and some other things.

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:22.000
I just give us a bill and we'll pay for that.

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:26.000
And I guess something rose up in me said, we don't want your money.

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:29.000
We didn't come down here.

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:30.000
We don't money.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:37.000
We said, we never saw these documents that you said we refused to sign or didn't sign.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:42.000
We didn't hear about them until you started broadcasting.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:47.000
What you're doing, but we're not going to waste our time and your time.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:50.000
The doctor came, will come.

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
He will speak.

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:55.000
And I said, we'll have to tell the world about what you did.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:57.000
We'll tell the truth.

00:50:57.000 --> 00:50:59.000
I said nothing but the truth, so help me God.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:00.000
So help me.

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:06.000
God, we walked out and at that time,

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:09.000
he's been in Seattle and it's at the time.

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
Not any went the time.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:15.000
How do I went to Seattle until 1967?

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:21.000
Oh, well, this was prior to I-5 going through downtown Seattle.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:28.000
So the First Presbyterian Church up at 8th and Madison.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:34.000
And we walked right down the hill to the...

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:37.000
Oh, what's that building?

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:40.000
It's Ac Deer to know.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:47.000
But since then, the freeway has taken a strange route through downtown.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:53.000
Took the properties that some people wanted to get rid of and get a good price wall.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:52:00.000
But we went right down there and put money down on having the event there.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:04.000
And it did happen there.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:13.000
Just before I retired in 1998,

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:19.000
in the mail I had, there was an on-broad

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:23.000
and said, First Presbyterian Church.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:27.000
And I looked at it and I tossed it in the circular pile.

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:30.000
And something told me to go back and look at it

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:35.000
because it wasn't a label on it was typed.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:38.000
I said, well, what would these folks want?

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:44.000
And I opened it and the content of the letter was simply that

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:50.000
37 or 38 years ago, or even justice was done to your church

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:55.000
and to you and relish to apologize for that.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:59.000
Well, I got it on the phone and called.

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:02.000
The minister told me I'd actually come down and be here.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:05.000
He said, I think I'm a little younger than you all come up there.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:07.000
Well, we had 19th and Madison.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:13.000
There was 8th. Madison, so he came up.

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:19.000
And I told him, you know, a lot of whites say that this is unnecessary

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
because their ancestors never owned slaves

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:26.000
so we don't owe you an apology for anything.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:29.000
That's what Summiff said.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:35.000
And I said, you don't even apologize for white privilege.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:38.000
The speed of certain things are automatically yours

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:43.000
because of who you are, but we appreciated what the young man did.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:46.000
I don't think he's there now.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:51.000
But he was just in...

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.000
He was at my retirement.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:56.000
Ben Quid and I introduced him to the congregation

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:58.000
and others who were there.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:02.000
And thanked him for what they set up some relationship

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:04.000
between the young people.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:12.000
But it's as glad to see that something like that did happen.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:15.000
If 38, 39 years later.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:18.000
Yeah, better late than never.

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:21.000
But we still have to make correct and so it is.

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:25.000
It hasn't happened for over years ago, 100 years ago.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
It is necessary.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.000
And I'm still believing reparations

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
that don't have to be given me any money

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:39.000
but set up the Japanese were...

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:42.000
Because what happens to them is Pearl Harbor.

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:46.000
As a result of Pearl Harbor.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:50.000
They've been apologies and financial things

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:57.000
because I was told we can see from up here

