01:17:24.000 --> 01:17:27.000
things seemed...

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:29.000
It appeared to be...

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:31.000
It appeared to be, but...

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:33.000
But I'm guessing there was something below this.

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:34.000
Yeah, there was.

01:17:34.000 --> 01:17:39.000
I remember some places where we tried to eat.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:43.000
And they had to remind them that they weren't where they came from.

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:46.000
They may not want to feed me.

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:49.000
And if they didn't want to feed me,

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:52.000
I didn't want to eat their food.

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:55.000
It happened because I don't know.

01:17:55.000 --> 01:18:00.000
I know some of the things that were done.

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:04.000
In retaliation to that sort of thing,

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:08.000
I wouldn't want to eat any of the tainted food myself.

01:18:09.000 --> 01:18:13.000
But there were...

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:17.000
We had difficulty finding houses at first,

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:22.000
not this one, but I didn't want to stay in the church process.

01:18:22.000 --> 01:18:27.000
And we needed all of that to expand the church.

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:33.000
But I would call around to see what I'd seen in the Virgin Mary's house.

01:18:33.000 --> 01:18:36.000
I wasn't calling and asking about it.

01:18:36.000 --> 01:18:39.000
Somebody would ask me, are you colored?

01:18:39.000 --> 01:18:41.000
I think you just asked straight out.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:43.000
Yeah, maybe they could get out of my voice.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:46.000
I tried to mask.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:49.000
It belonged to my wife, Carl.

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:52.000
She was in education.

01:18:52.000 --> 01:18:56.000
She was a purist when it came to language.

01:18:56.000 --> 01:19:02.000
She was more English and a speech and pronunciation than the British themselves.

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:09.000
So then we saw so much time that when we showed up,

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:11.000
there was a different story.

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:14.000
So that was here.

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:20.000
That was right here in Seattle.

01:19:20.000 --> 01:19:26.000
We did have...

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:31.000
We did have some strikes and other things against

01:19:31.000 --> 01:19:33.000
the big department store downtown.

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:36.000
Years ago, it was Frederick & Nelson.

01:19:36.000 --> 01:19:41.000
Nordstrom's now in the building where Frederick & Nelson was.

01:19:41.000 --> 01:19:45.000
But when we marched on Frederick & Nelson,

01:19:45.000 --> 01:19:51.000
that opened them up to employment.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:54.000
Who were your allies in this kind of work?

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:57.000
Were Seattle organized at all?

01:19:57.000 --> 01:19:59.000
Oh, yeah.

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:01.000
What was your urban age?

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:05.000
The NAACP.

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:11.000
There was...

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:13.000
Did CORE have a print of them here?

01:20:13.000 --> 01:20:14.000
Later.

01:20:14.000 --> 01:20:17.000
Yeah.

01:20:17.000 --> 01:20:19.000
They had a presence later on.

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:24.000
But historically, the NAACP and...

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:30.000
And urban age on the ground so to speak.

01:20:30.000 --> 01:20:36.000
What was it?

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:43.000
I know that in 1963, you were part of the group that organized what became known as the CACRC.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:45.000
If you could tell us what that was.

01:20:45.000 --> 01:20:47.000
What was that for?

01:20:47.000 --> 01:20:53.000
This was the community group that drew from other groups to fully all to do.

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:59.000
To fully all together to organize the essential area.

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:02.000
Yeah, exactly.

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:06.000
I only wrote down that.

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:13.000
The essential area.

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:18.000
Central Area Civil Rights Committee.

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:19.000
Yeah.

01:21:20.000 --> 01:21:26.000
That was made up of all the groups.

01:21:26.000 --> 01:21:33.000
As a Rev. John Adams, who was the pastor first in me at the time,

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:36.000
was the most successful leader of that group.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:42.000
He's now a retired bishop in the AME church living in Atlanta.

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:47.000
And did you quite a few things?

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:52.000
Has school strike?

01:21:52.000 --> 01:21:56.000
You can stay at home from school.

01:21:56.000 --> 01:22:01.000
The schools were segregated prior to that?

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:03.000
additionally.

01:22:03.000 --> 01:22:09.000
They weren't the best.

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:14.000
They thought they were.

01:22:14.000 --> 01:22:26.000
I'm a wife of Spanner Hill, Korea, here in Seattle in the school district.

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:38.000
Yeah, it was under the auspices of the Central Area Civil Rights Committee that a lot of good was done in organizing the museum.

01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:42.000
And people.

01:22:42.000 --> 01:22:49.000
And we really had two fronts.

01:22:49.000 --> 01:23:01.000
One was working in harmony with groups that were struggling in the South

01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:14.000
and also dealing with whatever vestiges of segregation and racism we encountered here.

01:23:14.000 --> 01:23:23.000
Someone said at that time the difference between the South and the North,

01:23:23.000 --> 01:23:30.000
the South didn't care how close blacks and whites got so wrong,

01:23:30.000 --> 01:23:33.000
we didn't get too high.

01:23:33.000 --> 01:23:39.000
The North didn't care how high we got provided we didn't get too close.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:47.000
So I think that sums it up to a great extent.

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:50.000
They had a state.

01:23:50.000 --> 01:23:54.000
The state had a group.

01:23:54.000 --> 01:23:57.000
I'm trying to think of it.

01:23:57.000 --> 01:24:05.000
I'm not trying to say it's a private name, but the last part was against racial discrimination or something of that effect.

01:24:05.000 --> 01:24:10.000
And they would deal with things legally.

01:24:10.000 --> 01:24:13.000
They were kind of slow in.

01:24:13.000 --> 01:24:20.000
Of course you had to prove that you had really been mistreated.

01:24:20.000 --> 01:24:26.000
So there was a need for other kinds of activities.

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:32.000
But I think the big march on.

01:24:32.000 --> 01:24:38.000
Frederick & Nelson really opened up a lot of George R. Remember one fellow.

01:24:38.000 --> 01:24:40.000
He was a member of our congregation.

01:24:40.000 --> 01:24:45.000
He was had a critical of me and my participation.

01:24:45.000 --> 01:24:49.000
And told us we shouldn't march against Frederick & Nelson.

01:24:49.000 --> 01:24:55.000
But when we did it and was successful, he was one of the first persons to apply it for a job.

01:24:55.000 --> 01:25:05.000
There's always going to be some people who think you're too radical.

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:08.000
And then there's others who think you're not radical enough.

01:25:08.000 --> 01:25:18.000
And so I know that towards the end of the 60, 68, 69, there were some more radical groups that began to deform and see out including a chapter of the Black Panther.

01:25:18.000 --> 01:25:25.000
And how did you all work with them or had it?

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:30.000
Not too well.

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:32.000
Go ahead.

01:25:32.000 --> 01:25:42.000
What was the access to Congress?

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:45.000
Could have been a generation, could have been a...

01:25:45.000 --> 01:25:53.000
thought we were moving too slow or some of their white supporters.

01:25:53.000 --> 01:26:05.000
We felt that we needed to get out the way so they could come more to the poor.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:15.000
And some of us tried to ignore it because it looked like somebody tried to play off one group against the other.

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:19.000
And they hadn't gotten up off of anything.

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:33.000
And I think the Panthers could have been more effective than they were.

01:26:33.000 --> 01:26:39.000
Did you understand where they were coming from or at all?

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:42.000
Did it seem like just the wrong approach to you?

01:26:42.000 --> 01:26:48.000
I thought that they were coming from.

01:26:48.000 --> 01:27:03.000
Then some of them saw the ministers as they entered more than discrimination.

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:17.000
And some of us were the targets of some of their anger and venom.

01:27:17.000 --> 01:27:28.000
But some of them were matured, grown up.

01:27:28.000 --> 01:27:32.000
But they're still here.

01:27:32.000 --> 01:27:35.000
Time moves on.

01:27:35.000 --> 01:27:39.000
Can you tell us a little bit?

01:27:39.000 --> 01:27:41.000
I think we'll probably wrap up pretty soon.

01:27:41.000 --> 01:27:46.000
But about some of your other work, your later work.

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:53.000
And particularly interested in your work with Liberty Bank or the Industrial Center.

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:57.000
And I know that there's now the Samuel Berry McKinney Manor.

01:27:57.000 --> 01:28:01.000
If you could tell us about that.

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:14.000
One of the things I know when I came, one of the things that interested me was that the church wanted to build.

01:28:14.000 --> 01:28:17.000
That's something I wanted to do.

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:19.000
So those two things can hook up.

01:28:19.000 --> 01:28:21.000
We can go forward.

01:28:21.000 --> 01:28:26.000
We need to buy up some land that we did.

01:28:26.000 --> 01:28:35.000
And we were able to build a new church by our land so we could have parking so much city.

01:28:35.000 --> 01:28:42.000
If a church can park the cars and babysit the children, you can grow them.

01:28:42.000 --> 01:28:46.000
Otherwise, they will plateau.

01:28:46.000 --> 01:28:49.000
So we tried to do that.

01:28:49.000 --> 01:29:02.000
And we looked at our sister church down the street, first seeing me that now completely surrounded by apartments.

01:29:02.000 --> 01:29:07.000
People coming back to the city who ran away from it.

01:29:07.000 --> 01:29:11.000
That's what gentrification is all about.

01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:15.000
I was talking about poor whites coming back.

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:18.000
This is gentry.

01:29:18.000 --> 01:29:22.000
We know the difference.

01:29:22.000 --> 01:29:28.000
And we were able to Mount Zion Baptist Church Baptist Church (to) buy quite a bit of property.

01:29:28.000 --> 01:29:32.000
And I think that hated in the...

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:33.000
I have them.

01:29:33.000 --> 01:29:40.000
So one of the first things I did when it came was to set it up so the church could back the land.

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:45.000
We also established a credit union in the church.

01:29:45.000 --> 01:29:55.000
So people could take care of their own needs and also when we got ready to build the sanctuary unit,

01:29:55.000 --> 01:30:00.000
we didn't get money from one single local bank.

01:30:00.000 --> 01:30:08.000
So we did have the help of the American Baptist Home Mission Society as well as people borrowing from the credit union.

01:30:08.000 --> 01:30:11.000
So the local banks just flat-out refused?

01:30:11.000 --> 01:30:15.000
Yeah, on that part.

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:23.000
But then we took advantage of some of the government programs and that's how we were able to build the manner.

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:30.000
Now another piece, it's 22nd and Jackson.

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:34.000
It's a Seattle Vocational Institute.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:45.000
But that venue was initially the Seattle OIC Opportunities Industrialization Center.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:54.000
That after President of that, Dr. Rev. Leon H. Sullivan of Philadelphia started that movement,

01:30:54.000 --> 01:30:59.000
the training that educate people.

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:02.000
We put up that building.

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:06.000
But when (President Ronald) Reagan became President, he pulled a rug out from under.

01:31:06.000 --> 01:31:12.000
A lot of those community efforts set better themselves.

01:31:12.000 --> 01:31:22.000
And Jim McDermott, who's a representative from the state, stepped in

01:31:22.000 --> 01:31:29.000
and where we were on the verge of bankruptcy, he had the state to take over.

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:38.000
That didn't give that to wipe out any debt that we owed and also to the community colleges

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:45.000
to have their facility, which is there now.

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:53.000
They also, another program, a CAMP.

01:31:53.000 --> 01:32:03.000
And now there are others who have come to take it over and change the name from Camp to Setahoe.

01:32:03.000 --> 01:32:06.000
They say they're there to help the new poor.

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:07.000
Setahoe.

01:32:07.000 --> 01:32:12.000
Or something like that.

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:19.000
So I've been involved in a lot of those community efforts.

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:23.000
I was a part of the group that helped organize the Liberty Bank,

01:32:23.000 --> 01:32:32.000
which later went out of business and the facility that it built in 24th and union.

01:32:32.000 --> 01:32:37.000
I rode by that a day, I made being a living trouble.

01:32:37.000 --> 01:32:41.000
Because they said they were going to close that facility.

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:46.000
And they got a safety deposit box.

01:32:46.000 --> 01:32:51.000
And I don't know what it's going to happen to.

01:32:51.000 --> 01:32:58.000
Tomorrow I'm going to get on that very thing.

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:06.000
So I have been involved in doing what I feel is a lot of good around the city and community.

01:33:06.000 --> 01:33:13.000
Not only protesting, but also building.

01:33:13.000 --> 01:33:21.000
And you see all these different kinds of works on different fronts as connected as part of the same body?

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:30.000
Yes, and one of the questions, one of the problems we have to face now is how you have community

01:33:30.000 --> 01:33:37.000
when you no longer have neighborhood.

01:33:37.000 --> 01:33:47.000
I'm looking at how the Jewish community has dealt with that and some of the Asian communities,

01:33:47.000 --> 01:33:49.000
where they are scattered and may not.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:55.000
There are some points where they are united.

01:33:55.000 --> 01:33:59.000
I know I spoke at the church.

01:33:59.000 --> 01:34:05.000
I speak annually. They called it Passing Maritra Sunday, but there was a couple of years ago.

01:34:05.000 --> 01:34:08.000
When I was speaking at the I did just hit me.

01:34:08.000 --> 01:34:13.000
I asked how many of you live within a mile of the church.

01:34:13.000 --> 01:34:19.000
And the further I got away from there, here we are, it's in my house.

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:23.000
The more people we encountered.

01:34:23.000 --> 01:34:27.000
And I began to think about that.

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:31.000
It would have been the opposite when the church was first.

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:34.000
Well, no.

01:34:34.000 --> 01:34:42.000
The church moved to 19th and Madison in 1920.

01:34:42.000 --> 01:34:47.000
And the built in old, built in essentially there.

01:34:47.000 --> 01:34:53.000
Then we replaced in 1974.

01:34:53.000 --> 01:35:05.000
We put an education here at first, but there were those who ran from the neighborhood.

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:12.000
But historically, there were two areas.

01:35:12.000 --> 01:35:20.000
One off of Madison, 2425, was a pocket of blacks and then over on Jackson,

01:35:20.000 --> 01:35:23.000
was another pocket.

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:29.000
And I've seen those two grow together, which are called the other central area.

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:41.000
Now, but I think there were some who were glad to see it change because

01:35:41.000 --> 01:35:48.000
too much political power was being assessed, was being developed there.

01:35:48.000 --> 01:35:53.000
Many of the churches are there. There's something that's springing up in other places.

01:35:53.000 --> 01:35:56.000
But that was a historical community.

01:35:56.000 --> 01:36:06.000
And I noticed that on Sunday we have people, members who live out this way in North-Answer.

01:36:06.000 --> 01:36:11.000
And after church they like to mix them being able to, because I haven't seen,

01:36:11.000 --> 01:36:16.000
folks that they used to see at the grocery store don't see them anymore.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:27.000
In fact, when I first came up on another method of ministries of people,

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:34.000
there were several credit, good-sized supermarkets in the central area.

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:40.000
And sometimes when I was in some of them on business people would come up to me

01:36:40.000 --> 01:36:44.000
from the church to ask questions or someone said,

01:36:44.000 --> 01:36:49.000
I won't be there soon to put this in here as my offering,

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:51.000
to put in.

01:36:51.000 --> 01:36:59.000
And so I just started some Friday evenings and early Saturdays just hanging around the supermarket.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:03.000
And people would be very, very come up.

01:37:03.000 --> 01:37:07.000
But they've torn up a lot of that.

01:37:07.000 --> 01:37:14.000
And the largest number of blacks moving into the central area now

01:37:14.000 --> 01:37:20.000
are from various sections of the African continent.

01:37:20.000 --> 01:37:24.000
So that's it just before I retired.

01:37:24.000 --> 01:37:28.000
I was asked to come to a meeting.

01:37:29.000 --> 01:37:37.000
And you know how some people are when they think they have a heavy drop on you.

01:37:37.000 --> 01:37:49.000
Do you know that African Americans are now the number three non-white group in the community?

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:57.000
And other things I was supposed to, I guess I was supposed to have been stressed out on the floor crying and hungry.

01:37:58.000 --> 01:38:06.000
And if he'd gone through that, he wanted a reaction because he, I don't think he was getting the one.

01:38:06.000 --> 01:38:17.000
He expected, I said, well, first of all, you say that his panics are now the largest single group.

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:24.000
I said, but the thing that unites the Hispanic community as unsuspecting is not ethnicity but tone.

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:28.000
So you have a lot of black Hispanics.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:32.000
Now how do you figure that? How do you deal with that?

01:38:32.000 --> 01:38:36.000
Well, that wasn't what he was expecting.

01:38:36.000 --> 01:38:39.000
And I said, now you're comparing us.

01:38:39.000 --> 01:38:44.000
All the blacks against, no, no.

01:38:44.000 --> 01:38:49.000
One segment of the blacks against, like all the Asians.

01:38:50.000 --> 01:38:57.000
And all the, that's on Latinos and Hispanics and not all.

01:38:57.000 --> 01:39:00.000
The United, depending upon where they came from.

01:39:00.000 --> 01:39:07.000
But part of Mexico they came from, where they came from, Chile, Argentina, Cuba.

01:39:07.000 --> 01:39:12.000
Say all of those things figure in.

01:39:13.000 --> 01:39:27.000
And then we talked about the, the people from the various parts of the African continent.

01:39:27.000 --> 01:39:30.000
I said, Africa is not a country.

01:39:30.000 --> 01:39:32.000
It's a continent.

01:39:32.000 --> 01:39:39.000
And you have as many varying differences of known blacks as you do, known, known whites.

01:39:40.000 --> 01:39:43.000
How do you know all of this?

01:39:43.000 --> 01:39:45.000
I said, how do you feel?

01:39:45.000 --> 01:39:49.000
I said, you know what, you claim you know.

01:39:49.000 --> 01:39:53.000
And we just want to set the record straight.

01:39:53.000 --> 01:39:57.000
So you, you know what's going on.

01:39:57.000 --> 01:40:04.000
I told them that some of the Ethiopians,

01:40:04.000 --> 01:40:09.000
before they built a, that church had certain events in our church.

01:40:09.000 --> 01:40:17.000
So I was aware of this mall, but for Haitian churches in West Seattle.

01:40:17.000 --> 01:40:21.000
I said, well, you didn't know that.

01:40:21.000 --> 01:40:33.000
But what is the Central Area is very desirous.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:36.000
It's a piece of property.

01:40:36.000 --> 01:40:38.000
My wife found this place.

01:40:38.000 --> 01:40:40.000
But I was setting people on.

01:40:40.000 --> 01:40:44.000
I said, you're property in the Central Area is valuable.

01:40:44.000 --> 01:40:50.000
Then I kept a mailbox up there in the 23rd Union in the east.

01:40:50.000 --> 01:40:57.000
Once a week or twice a month someone said to me, aren't you the fellow that told us not to sell our property?

01:40:57.000 --> 01:41:00.000
I said, yes, but you left.

01:41:00.000 --> 01:41:05.000
I said, well, did you see the picture of the Godfather?

01:41:05.000 --> 01:41:11.000
I said, yes, and I was given an offer I couldn't refuse.

01:41:11.000 --> 01:41:24.000
So we, in 1958, moved away with you there for 42 years on in the Madrona.

01:41:24.000 --> 01:41:34.000
And then my wife found that we needed another place.

01:41:34.000 --> 01:41:37.000
She found this.

01:41:37.000 --> 01:41:41.000
And if a wife is happy, you can make it.

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:43.000
That's a picture right there.

01:41:43.000 --> 01:41:47.000
She passed in August.

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:49.000
But...

01:41:49.000 --> 01:41:54.000
And was a real partner of yours in your ministry and after that?

01:41:54.000 --> 01:42:01.000
If she had a own life and education, I didn't fool with...

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:05.000
She was the expert there.

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:08.000
And she found this place.

01:42:08.000 --> 01:42:12.000
And left a mark on it.

01:42:12.000 --> 01:42:15.000
The people we bought the house from, we know them.

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:18.000
They came back one day and they didn't recognize it.

01:42:18.000 --> 01:42:21.000
She put these floors in.

01:42:21.000 --> 01:42:24.000
The windows.

01:42:24.000 --> 01:42:27.000
Because they used to rattle them.

01:42:27.000 --> 01:42:29.000
They first came in.

01:42:29.000 --> 01:42:33.000
Got a nice view here.

01:42:33.000 --> 01:42:38.000
Well, anything that we didn't talk about or that I didn't ask,

01:42:38.000 --> 01:42:43.000
they would like to...

01:42:43.000 --> 01:42:56.000
I can rattle them.

01:42:56.000 --> 01:43:02.000
Well, what could it be some areas that you feel

01:43:02.000 --> 01:43:05.000
that you should have been touched to deal with it?

01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:08.000
I think we covered quite a lot.

01:43:08.000 --> 01:43:11.000
I know, but I made a list.

01:43:11.000 --> 01:43:16.000
Some of the main things.

01:43:16.000 --> 01:43:20.000
Well, you have a long perspective on the movement.

01:43:20.000 --> 01:43:25.000
What's happening in your wife's time.

01:43:25.000 --> 01:43:28.000
Can you say something about what progress has been made

01:43:28.000 --> 01:43:32.000
or what still needs to be done?

01:43:33.000 --> 01:43:37.000
A lot of progress has been made.

01:43:37.000 --> 01:43:44.000
Some people feel that Obama's election should sum it all up.

01:43:44.000 --> 01:43:50.000
But I have never seen or expected some of the reaction.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:53.000
Some of the things that have been said about Obama

01:43:53.000 --> 01:43:59.000
that if they've been said about Bush who I feel was the worst president

01:43:59.000 --> 01:44:04.000
we've ever had from the beginning up to this time.

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:15.000
They tolerated him and Obama is bent over too much after he ever tried to plaking.

01:44:15.000 --> 01:44:19.000
Folks who have no intention of working with him

01:44:19.000 --> 01:44:27.000
because they would rather see the country suffer than for him to claim any credit.

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:34.000
It's been a good that has been done.

01:44:34.000 --> 01:44:41.000
And I just want to...

01:44:41.000 --> 01:44:46.000
I think you could take a couple of pages from Roosevelt's book.

01:44:46.000 --> 01:44:48.000
You don't cooperate.

01:44:48.000 --> 01:44:50.000
You're just...

01:44:50.000 --> 01:44:54.000
We'll suffer.

01:44:54.000 --> 01:45:10.000
I can see people now trying to get into the position to play blacks and Latinos off one against each other.

01:45:10.000 --> 01:45:20.000
But that's an old trick and...

01:45:20.000 --> 01:45:26.000
Many things were pulled to tragedy feet of Obama

01:45:26.000 --> 01:45:32.000
but they did not count on the coming together.

01:45:32.000 --> 01:45:39.000
The folks they ignored and still think that they can just talk to them

01:45:39.000 --> 01:45:48.000
and talk to other groups and they were born in with them.

01:45:48.000 --> 01:45:59.000
The Asian communities are some of the most highly trained and educated in the country.

01:45:59.000 --> 01:46:05.000
And you can't buy them or would be yes.

01:46:05.000 --> 01:46:17.000
You have to put a percent up and it's becoming more that way with some of the Hispanic Latino communities.

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:32.000
And we need to all come together and find out who really wants to go in the direction we feel is best for the nation.

01:46:32.000 --> 01:46:45.000
And I think they found out that many of the people 30 in London have more in common.

01:46:45.000 --> 01:46:56.000
Than the Tea Party as whoever they are.

01:46:56.000 --> 01:47:04.000
It's interesting it's going to be more interesting as we go along.

01:47:04.000 --> 01:47:15.000
And I'm just curious to where Obama is going to take us.

01:47:15.000 --> 01:47:19.000
I'm really going to go along with him.

01:47:19.000 --> 01:47:31.000
And I think most people who think for a capable of thinking would you likewise?

01:47:31.000 --> 01:47:43.000
I also had the feeling that there were those who say that we experimented in the backman was president now.

01:47:43.000 --> 01:47:48.000
It's time for a woman to be president.

01:47:48.000 --> 01:47:58.000
I'm sure that Mrs. Clinton would make a good president.

01:47:59.000 --> 01:48:01.000
That's the way we're headed.

01:48:01.000 --> 01:48:04.000
And I think we are.

01:48:04.000 --> 01:48:07.000
There's hope for us.

01:48:07.000 --> 01:48:16.000
And I'm just praying every day that the nuts and the fools out there.

01:48:16.000 --> 01:48:25.000
We feel their lives depend upon the right to have a gun and shoot it.

01:48:26.000 --> 01:48:32.000
Or be seen with one or come to their senses.

01:48:32.000 --> 01:48:43.000
I'm just praying that since which is not common to everybody, we'll prevail.

01:48:43.000 --> 01:48:50.000
So what are you going to do with all this stuff?

01:48:50.000 --> 01:48:57.000
Well, it's going to, well first of all, we just thank you very much again for sharing your story with us.

01:48:57.000 --> 01:49:00.000
I'm for your work.

01:49:00.000 --> 01:49:03.000
The material is all going to go into the Library of Congress.

01:49:03.000 --> 01:49:13.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
